        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>zitherlike chordophones: bowed [300224197], zitherlike chordophones [300224193], chordophones [300041641], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Single-string zitherlike chordophones with a slender, three-sided body made of thin boards tapering to the top, and a unique bridge, one of the feet of which does not rest on the belly of the instrument but is suspended a hairsbreadth above it, so that it drums rapidly against it when played. Common from the 15th to the mid-18th century.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Cordófonos tipo cítara de una sola cuerda, con un cuerpo esbelto triángular hecho de planchas de madera delgadas estrechándose hacia el extremo superior, y un puente único, uno de cuyos pies no descansa en el vientre sino que está suspendido apenas sobre él, de manera que lo golpea rápidamente cuando se ejecuta el instrumento. Comunes desde el siglo XV hasta mediados del siglo XVIII.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Snaarinstrumenten met een slanke, driekantige, spitstoelopende klankkast van dunne plankjes, kam waarvan één van de voeten een fractie boven het bovenblad hangt, waardoor de kam daartegenaan roffelt tijdens het bespelen, 1 snaar; 15de eeuw tot midden 18de eeuw.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052453/Algemene muziekencyclopedie (1961)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指類似齊特琴的單弦弦鳴樂器，具有以細長木頭製成的三面琴身，琴身呈椎狀，由下向上漸細；琴橋獨特，其中一隻琴橋腳並未貼於琴肚上，而是稍微懸於琴肚正上方，所以彈奏時，琴橋會快速敲擊琴肚。常見於十五至十八世紀中葉。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Einsaitiges Zitherinstrument mit einem schlanken, dreieckigen Korpus aus dünnen Brettern, die sich zur Spitze hin verjüngen, und einem besonderen Steg, bei dem einer der beiden Füße nicht auf der Instrumentendecke ruht, sondern eine Haaresbreite über der Decke schwebt, sodass er beim Spielen periodisch aufschlägt. Verbreitet vom 15. Jahrhundert bis zur Mitte des 18. Jahrhunderts.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
